A considerable number of facts have now been brought forward in regard to the relationship of the manuscripts in group (IV) and those most closely allied with them. To these facts may be added what has been said above on pp. 64 and 66 about the changed order 0f subjects or omission of certain porticus of text in CF, LT, CC, LD, W. Several of the members of (IV) were seen to be involved in the matter of leaving blank spaces at certain points in the text (p. 78 above). Yet all that can be learned from all this information is that these particular manuscripts constitute, at least for the most part, a group which, though more or less inter-related at places, follows no line of relationship which is either constant or well defined. They represent no one tradition. Constant copying and recopying of texts derived from a mixed ancestry has produced a medley of traditions. Unless the gaps in the lines of descent are filled by the discovery of new manuscripts we shall never be able to know just what has happened.
